From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Sun, 21 Jun 2026 17:33:46 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] xargs: run built commands through brush
 (builtins/functions/scripts), not exec
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Ports xargs to dispatch each command it builds through `Shell::run_argv`
instead of spawning a `std::process::Command`. So `… | xargs cmd` now runs a
shell builtin, a function, or a script — all with the box's snooping — exactly
like env/nice. Before, `xargs type` / `xargs <function>` were "command not
found"; now they work.

Mechanism (new `builtin_exec` module): findutils is synchronous and run_argv is
async on a non-Send shell, so findutils runs on a worker THREAD and submits
each built argv over a channel; an async executor on the builtin's task runs it
via run_argv on a SUBSHELL CLONE (per-command env/cwd don't leak — the
one-process-per-command model) and replies with the exit code. The xargs
builtin becomes an async `builtins::Command` (like env); the findutils fork's
execution is abstracted behind an `ExecChild` ticket (`XargsIo::submit`), with
the standalone binary keeping its `std::process::Command` path.

`-P` parallelism is the executor running several submissions concurrently
(FuturesUnordered on the one task) — and it now matches brush's OWN
`(cmd)& … & wait` semantics exactly: external commands parallelize, in-process
builtins serialize on the shell's task. Verified: `sleep & … & wait` (sleep
builtin) is 4s in plain brush too, while `sh -c "sleep 1" & …` is 1s; xargs -P
mirrors both. The earlier process-pool made `xargs -P sleep` parallel only
because it exec'd a binary — inconsistent with the shell it lives in.

Verified in a box shim: builtin dispatch (`xargs type` → "shell builtin"),
shell function, shebang script, external + logical cwd (`find | xargs cat`),
exit-code propagation (false → 123). find is unchanged (ported next). 93
engine tests pass.

